ed the rest.\n\n  Line 81: - Four code-graph-side adoptions: soft-delete tombstone audit, shared BFS consolidation, `why_included` edge-chain breadcrumbs, optional BM25 symbol resolver.\n\n  Line 99: | `system-code-graph/.../lib/code-graph-db.ts`, `handlers/scan.ts`, `handlers/status.ts` | Modify | 006 | Soft-delete tombstone lineage / status counts |\n\n  Line 119: | 6 | 006-codegraph-tombstone-audit/ | Transfer #4: bounded soft-delete tombstone lineage for stale code-graph nodes/edges | Complete |\n\n  Line 141: | 006-codegraph-tombstone-audit | (none) | Independent; bounded/default-off; ships standalone | Phase `--strict` validate |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/review/lineages/gpt-2/iterations/iteration-001.md:\n  Line 73: Review security-sensitive guardrails around provenance, env flags, tombstone persistence, and trace payloads.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/review/lineages/gpt-2/iterations/iteration-002.md:\n  Line 5: Reviewed trust boundaries and persistence guardrails in advisor provenance writes, feedback calibration shadow records, code-graph tombstones, and trace payload gates.\n\n  Line 45: - Default-on audit writes: code-graph tombstones require `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONES === 'true'` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/lib/code-graph-db.ts:232-234].\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/review/lineages/gpt-2/prompts/iteration-002.md:\n  Line 7: Scope: provenance guard, shadow feedback persistence, tombstones, trace outputs.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/review/lineages/gpt-2/deep-review-strategy.md:\n  Line 13: - [x] Security: provenance guard, default-off shadow calibration, tombstone gating, and trace payload surfaces reviewed.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/review/lineages/gpt-1/iterations/iteration-003.md:\n  Line 23: - **F003**: Parent phase packet still claims scaffold-only planned status while child phases are completed. The parent metadata says `Status | Planned` [SOURCE: `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/spec.md:51`] and the parent narrative says all nine phases are planned, scaffold-only, and no advisor/code-graph source has been modified [SOURCE: `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/spec.md:71`, `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/spec.md:87`]. Child phases now report completed implementation, for example 001 [SOURCE: `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/001-advisor-observability/spec.md:49`], 006 [SOURCE: `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit/spec.md:55`], and 009 [SOURCE: `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/009-codegraph-bm25-symbol-resolver/spec.md:54`]. Parent graph metadata still derives `status: planned` and only lists `spec.md` as key file [SOURCE: `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/graph-metadata.json:44-47`]. This misleads resume/search/status consumers and hides active integration debt from the parent packet.\n\n  Line 36:     \".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/018-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit/spec.md:55\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/review/lineages/gpt-1/deep-review-strategy.md:\n  Line 50: - No tombstone retention finding was recorded: the status path and retention pruning are present in inspected code.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/022-hybrid-rag-fusion/008-hydra-db-based-features/plan.md:\n  Line 99: - [x] Fix shared-space owner enforcement and retention sweep deletion routing.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit/spec.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Feature Specification: Soft-delete tombstone audit for stale code-graph nodes/edges\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"The code graph hard-deletes nodes/edges during reindex and stale cleanup, so there is no answer to why did this edge disappear. Adopt 027's tombstone audit lineage, bounded/default-off since the graph is rebuildable.\"\n\n  Line 5:   - \"code graph tombstones\"\n\n  Line 6:   - \"soft delete audit lineage\"\n\n  Line 13:     packet_pointer: \"system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 16:     recent_action: \"Implemented bounded default-off code-graph tombstone audit lineage\"\n\n  Line 23:       - \".opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts\"\n\n  Line 26:       session_id: \"scaffold-scaffold/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 31:       - \"Use a bounded row-level tombstone table created only when SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONES=true.\"\n\n  Line 35: # Feature Specification: Phase 6: codegraph-tombstone-audit\n\n  Line 62: | **Source transfers** | Analysis #4 (soft-delete tombstones / active-purgeable lifecycle) |\n\n  Line 63: | **Handoff Criteria** | Met: phase validates `--strict`; tombstone retention is bounded and default-off |\n\n  Line 73: **Scope Boundary**: The node/edge deletion paths in `lib/code-graph-db.ts` plus scan/status surfaces. Add bounded soft-delete tombstones (or status-only deletion counts) for stale-file, node, and edge cleanup. Default-off; the graph stays rebuildable.\n\n  Line 79: - Bounded tombstone lineage records file/node/edge removals with reason and timestamp when `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONES=true`.\n\n  Line 80: - Default-off behavior creates no tombstone table or rows; retention is bounded by `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONE_LIMIT`.\n\n  Line 92: The code graph hard-deletes nodes and edges during reindex and stale cleanup (`lib/code-graph-db.ts:692-704`, `:784-790`, `:890-905`), so after a file deletion or scan repair there is no way to answer \"why did this edge disappear?\". Memory's 027 tombstones preserve a deletion audit (`027 before-vs-after.md:91-101`). Because the code graph is rebuildable from source, tombstones are less critical than in memory and must stay bounded.\n\n  Line 104: - Bounded soft-delete tombstones (or status-only deletion counts) for stale node/edge cleanup.\n\n  Line 112: - Restoring tombstoned nodes/edges (audit, not recovery).\n\n  Line 118: | `system-code-graph/mcp_server/lib/code-graph-db.ts` (~:692-704, :784-790, :890-905) | Modify | Record bounded tombstone/reason at delete sites instead of pure hard-delete |\n\n  Line 120: | `system-code-graph/mcp_server/handlers/status.ts` | Modify | Surface bounded deletion/tombstone counts |\n\n  Line 121: | `system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts` | Create | Verify default-off, lineage, retention pruning, and live-query isolation |\n\n  Line 134: | REQ-001 | Retention is bounded; tombstones cannot grow unbounded | Test: exceed the configured bound; assert oldest tombstones are pruned and DB size stays bounded |\n\n  Line 135: | REQ-002 | Default-off: with the flag unset, delete behavior matches today's hard-delete | Scan/cleanup with flag off leaves no tombstone rows; status counts unchanged |\n\n  Line 141: | REQ-003 | A deleted edge/node records a reason answerable via status | After deleting a file and reindexing, the tombstone/status shows why the edge disappeared |\n\n  Line 142: | REQ-004 | Tombstones never affect live query results | Active queries ignore tombstoned rows; correctness unchanged vs hard-delete |\n\n  Line 163: | Risk | Tombstones leak into live queries | Med | REQ-004: active queries exclude tombstoned rows |\n\n  Line 171: - Answered: implemented bounded row-level tombstones plus status summary counts, not full graph time-travel.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit/plan.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Implementation Plan: Phase 6: codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Bounded default-off tombstone audit lineage for code-graph stale node and edge cleanup.\"\n\n  Line 14:     packet_pointer: \"system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 17:     recent_action: \"Implemented default-off tombstone audit and verification\"\n\n  Line 24:       - \".opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts\"\n\n  Line 27:       session_id: \"scaffold-scaffold/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 34: # Implementation Plan: Phase 6: codegraph-tombstone-audit\n\n  Line 60: Implemented a feature-flagged tombstone audit table for code-graph stale cleanup. The table is created only when `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONES=true`, is bounded by `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONE_LIMIT`, and is summarized through scan/status without changing live graph queries.\n\n  Line 75: - [x] Tests passing: typecheck, build, tombstone/db/scan/status vitest suites\n\n  Line 88: - **`code_graph_tombstones` table**: Stores retained file/node/edge deletion rows only when tombstones are enabled.\n\n  Line 90: - **Scan/status summaries**: Surface retained tombstone counts and recent reasons without making status mutate the DB.\n\n  Line 93: When enabled, delete paths insert minimal tombstone rows before hard-deleting live graph rows. The retention prune keeps only the newest configured rows, and `getStats()` exposes the retained summary for scan and status responses.\n\n  Line 105: | `lib/code-graph-db.ts` | Owns SQLite schema, hard-delete paths, and stats | Added flag-gated tombstone schema, reason capture, retention prune, and stats summary | `code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts`, `code-graph-db.vitest.ts`, typecheck |\n\n  Line 106: | `handlers/scan.ts` | Removes missing tracked files during incremental/full scans | Passes explicit cleanup reasons and returns tombstone summary | `code-graph-scan.vitest.ts` |\n\n  Line 107: | `handlers/status.ts` | Reports graph health and counts | Adds read-only tombstone summary from stats | `code-graph-status-readiness-snapshot.vitest.ts` |\n\n  Line 112: - Invariant: tombstones live outside `code_nodes` and `code_edges`, so live queries cannot include tombstoned rows.\n\n  Line 126: - [x] Added default-off tombstone audit helpers and bounded retention\n\n  Line 128: - [x] Surfaced tombstone summary through scan/status\n\n  Line 131: - [x] New tombstone tests cover default-off, enabled lineage, retention pruning, and query isolation\n\n  Line 156: | Operator env flag `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONES` | Runtime config | Green | Keeps tombstones disabled by default |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit/tasks.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Tasks: Phase 6: codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Completed task list for bounded default-off code-graph tombstone audit lineage.\"\n\n  Line 13:     packet_pointer: \"system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 16:     recent_action: \"Completed tombstone audit implementation and verification\"\n\n  Line 23:       - \".opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts\"\n\n  Line 26:       session_id: \"scaffold-scaffold/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 33: # Tasks: Phase 6: codegraph-tombstone-audit\n\n  Line 67: - [x] T004 Add flag-gated tombstone schema and summary helpers (`lib/code-graph-db.ts`)\n\n  Line 68: - [x] T005 Add bounded retention pruning for tombstone rows (`lib/code-graph-db.ts`)\n\n  Line 70: - [x] T007 Surface scan/status tombstone summaries without changing live query tables (`handlers/scan.ts`, `handlers/status.ts`)\n\n  Line 78: - [x] T008 Add tombstone tests for enabled lineage and default-off behavior (`tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts`)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit/implementation-summary.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"Implementation Summary: codegraph tombstone audit\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Implemented bounded default-off tombstone audit lineage for code-graph stale node and edge cleanup.\"\n\n  Line 13:     packet_pointer: \"system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 16:     recent_action: \"Documented completed tombstone audit implementation\"\n\n  Line 23:       - \".opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts\"\n\n  Line 26:       session_id: \"scaffold-scaffold/006-codegraph-tombstone-audit\"\n\n  Line 45: | **Spec Folder** | 006-codegraph-tombstone-audit |\n\n  Line 55: You can now opt into a bounded deletion audit for code-graph cleanup and answer why retained nodes or edges disappeared. The default path still hard-deletes exactly as before: with `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONES` unset, no tombstone table is created and no tombstone rows are written.\n\n  Line 59: The code graph records file, node, and edge tombstones only when `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONES=true`. Each retained row stores the deletion kind, minimal identity fields, reason, and timestamp. Retention is count-bound by `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_TOMBSTONE_LIMIT`, defaulting to 100 rows and clamped to 10000.\n\n  Line 63: `getStats()` now includes a tombstone summary. `code_graph_scan` and `code_graph_status` expose retained counts by kind and reason plus recent retained tombstones, while live graph queries continue to read only `code_nodes` and `code_edges`.\n\n  Line 69: | `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/lib/code-graph-db.ts` | Modified | Added flag-gated tombstone schema, deletion capture, retention pruning, and stats summary |\n\n  Line 70: | `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/handlers/scan.ts` | Modified | Passed explicit cleanup reasons and included tombstone summary in scan results |\n\n  Line 71: | `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/handlers/status.ts` | Modified | Included tombstone summary in read-only status output |\n\n  Line 72: | `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts` | Created | Covered default-off behavior, enabled lineage, retention pruning, and query isolation |\n\n  Line 94: | Create the tombstone table only when enabled | This preserves default-off DB behavior and avoids default path-history growth. |\n\n  Line 96: | Keep tombstones outside live graph tables | Existing queries ignore tombstones without extra filters, preserving correctness and query performance. |\n\n  Line 111: | `npm test -- --run mcp_server/tests/code-graph-tombstones.vitest.ts mcp_server/tests/code-graph-db.vitest.ts mcp_server/tests/code-graph-scan.vitest.ts mcp_server/tests/code-graph-status-readiness-snapshot.vitest.ts` | PASS: 4 files, 55 tests |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/022-hybrid-rag-fusion/008-hydra-db-based-features/tasks.md:\n  Line 70: - [x] T021 [W:RUNTIME] Fix retention sweeps so deletion uses the passed database handle (`mcp_server/lib/governance/scope-governance.ts`, `mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-mutations.ts`, `mcp_server/tests/memory-governance.vitest.ts`)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/spec.md:\n  Line 82: - XCE feature transfers into skill-advisor and code-graph (observability, provenance guard, packed BM25, BFS, tombstone audit, why-included trace, symbol resolver).\n\n  Line 108: | 002 | `002-xce-feature-adoption-advisor-codegraph/` | XCE feature transfers into the skill-advisor and code-graph skills (observability, provenance, packed BM25, BFS, tombstones) | Complete |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/003-advisor-and-codegraph/001-causal-traversal-bfs/spec.md:\n  Line 80: - Causal WRITE lifecycle (tombstones, promoter, reconciliation) - owned by phase 003\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/022-hybrid-rag-fusion/008-hydra-db-based-features/implementation-summary.md:\n  Line 52: The March 20 2026 follow-up fixed three more reviewed runtime gaps in the shipped MCP surface. Governed retrieval scope now survives the MCP boundary end-to-end across `memory_search`, `memory_context`, and `memory_quick_search`; owner-only shared-space operations now enforce explicit actor identity plus owner authorization, with first-create auto-bootstrapping the creator as `owner`; and the FTS-backed graph channel now returns the same BM25-aware composite score it uses for SQL ranking instead of collapsing back to edge strength only. The earlier retention sweep database-handle fix remains in place, so retention sweeps now delete through the passed database handle rather than a global default path.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/022-hybrid-rag-fusion/008-hydra-db-based-features/research/deep-research-strategy.md:\n  Line 44: - Two runtime defects were fixed during closure: owner-only shared-space enforcement, retention sweep deletion routing\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/022-hybrid-rag-fusion/008-hydra-db-based-features/research/iterations/iteration-001-codex53.md:\n  Line 29: 6. **Architecture concern: retention.ts imports `getAllowedSharedSpaceIds` without checking `isSharedMemoryEnabled`** — At retention.ts:10,41, retention sweeps call `getAllowedSharedSpaceIds` directly. This is the same bypass issue identified by GPT-5.4 in shared-spaces.ts:423 — retention continues using shared-space allowlists even when shared memory is globally disabled.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/022-hybrid-rag-fusion/008-hydra-db-based-features/research/research.md:\n  Line 38: | B2 | shared-spaces.ts | `getAllowedSharedSpaceIds` bypasses global shared-memory disable | Retrieval pipeline and retention sweeps use shared-space allowlists even when feature is globally disabled | shared-spaces.ts:423; stage1-candidate-gen.ts:510; retention.ts:41 |\n\n  Line 121: 2. **Feature disable propagation is incomplete**: `isSharedMemoryEnabled` is checked by `assertSharedSpaceAccess` but not by `getAllowedSharedSpaceIds`. Downstream callers (retrieval pipeline, retention sweeps) can bypass the global disable.\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"retention_sweep|retention sweep|soft delete|tombstone|deleted_at","time":{"start":1781763553658,"end":1781763553704}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0942dbcf7e41749f016a338de15d9c8191aa9e96dd7207f621"}},"id":"prt_ed9623945001CFQu7fdEPVpfFB","sessionID":"ses_126a03146ffe6yn9ha3tk3Qb0n","messageID":"msg_ed961fbdb001k0VK3jzERUKhEC"}}
