{"type":"text","timestamp":1781763869346,"sessionID":"ses_126a03146ffe6yn9ha3tk3Qb0n","part":{"id":"prt_ed96708760017q3IhUPO89HH8X","messageID":"msg_ed966ec7200118EoGiTDU6CDfd","sessionID":"ses_126a03146ffe6yn9ha3tk3Qb0n","type":"text","text":"One doc anchor is still being confirmed directly before I cite it in the artifact; the rest of the packet is ready to write.","time":{"start":1781763868790,"end":1781763869343},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_00e78b354ebe4379016a338f1cc2d48191b0bf83a0efe0aa97","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781763870567,"sessionID":"ses_126a03146ffe6yn9ha3tk3Qb0n","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_NQpD4c5mP2OvUFaE5eJm1aJL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.0.1.3.md","offset":20,"limit":24},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.0.1.3.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n20: \n21: #### Memory merge could use stale data if the original changed during processing\n22: \n23: When merging two similar memories, the system reads the original memory, then sends it to an AI service for embedding generation (which involves a network call that can take seconds). After the embedding returns, the merge proceeds using the data it read earlier. But if another save modified or deleted that original memory during the embedding wait, the merge would overwrite the newer version with stale data -- or archive a record that no longer exists. Before committing the merge, the system now reloads the original memory inside the transaction and compares its content hash and last-modified timestamp against what it read before the embedding call. If the original changed, the merge aborts cleanly with a `predecessor_changed` status. If the original was deleted or archived by another process, it aborts with `predecessor_gone`. In both cases, the save falls through to the normal (non-merge) path instead of forcing stale data.\n24: \n25: \n26: #### Two index scans could start at the same time\n27: \n28: The system prevents index scans from running too frequently using a cooldown timer. But the check was a classic \"time-of-check vs time-of-use\" race: read the last scan time, check if enough time has passed, then update the timestamp. Two requests arriving in the same millisecond could both pass the check and both start scanning, wasting resources and potentially conflicting. The cooldown is now an atomic lease. A single database transaction checks the timer and reserves the scan slot in one step -- if the lease is fresh, the request is rejected immediately. The lease includes a crash-expiry timer, so if a scan process dies mid-way, the slot is automatically freed after 2 minutes instead of being permanently locked.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## Search Performance\n33: \n34: These fixes reduce redundant computation in the search pipeline. No search *results* change -- the same queries return the same answers, just faster.\n35: \n36: #### Fallback search was doing expensive work multiple times\n37: \n38: When a search doesn't find enough results, the system tries progressively looser criteria (\"fallback tiers\"). Each tier ran the *entire* search pipeline from scratch -- collecting candidates, fusing scores, reranking with the cross-encoder model, computing co-activation boosts, applying folder relevance, truncating by confidence, adding context headers, and trimming to token budget. The expensive post-processing stages (reranking, co-activation, token truncation) were running 2-3 times instead of once. The pipeline is now split into two phases. Phase 1 (collect and fuse candidates) runs for each fallback tier, building up the candidate pool. Phase 2 (reranking, co-activation, folder scoring, confidence filtering, context headers, token truncation) runs exactly once on the final merged candidate set after the last tier is chosen.\n39: \n40: \n41: #### Response size was estimated twice per result using slow serialization\n42: \n43: When deciding how many results fit in a response, the system estimates each result's \"token cost.\" It was calling this estimator twice per result -- once to compute the total, then again when greedily admitting results. Each call used `JSON.stringify()` to serialize the result object, which is surprisingly expensive for complex objects with nested metadata. Token estimates are now cached in a per-request map keyed by result ID. Each result is sized once and the cached value is reused. The estimator itself was rewritten to count known fields directly instead of serializing to JSON and measuring the string.\n\n(Showing lines 20-43 of 252. Use offset=44 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n#### Memory merge could use stale data if the original changed during processing\n\nWhen merging two similar memories, the system reads the original memory, then sends it to an AI service for embedding generation (which involves a network call that can take seconds). After the embedding returns, the merge proceeds using the data it read earlier. But if another save modified or deleted that original memory during the embedding wait, the merge would overwrite the newer version with stale data -- or archive a record that no longer exists. Before committing the merge, the system now reloads the original memory inside the transaction and compares its content hash and last-modified timestamp against what it read before the embedding call. If the original changed, the merge aborts cleanly with a `predecessor_changed` status. If the original was deleted or archived by another process, it aborts with `predecessor_gone`. In both cases, the save falls through to the normal (non-merge) path instead of forcing stale data.\n\n\n#### Two index scans could start at the same time\n\nThe system prevents index scans from running too frequently using a cooldown timer. But the check was a classic \"time-of-check vs time-of-use\" race: read the last scan time, check if enough time has passed, then update the timestamp. Two requests arriving in the same millisecond could both pass the check and both start scanning, wasting resources and potentially conflicting. The cooldown is now an atomic lease. A single database transaction checks the timer and reserves the scan slot in one step -- if the lease is fresh, the request is rejected immediately. The lease includes a crash-expiry timer, so if a scan process dies mid-way, the slot is automatically freed after 2 minutes instead of being permanently locked.\n\n---\n\n## Search Performance\n\nThese fixes reduce redundant computation in the search pipeline. No search *results* change -- the same queries return the same answers, just faster.\n\n#### Fallback search was doing expensive work multiple times\n\nWhen a search doesn't find enough results, the system tries progressively looser criteria (\"fallback tiers\"). Each tier ran the *entire* search pipeline from scratch -- collecting candidates, fusing scores, reranking with the cross-encoder model, computing co-activation boosts, applying folder relevance, truncating by confidence, adding context headers, and trimming to token budget. The expensive post-processing stages (reranking, co-activation, token truncation) were running 2-3 times instead of once. The pipeline is now split into two phases. Phase 1 (collect and fuse candidates) runs for each fallback tier, building up the candidate pool. Phase 2 (reranking, co-activation, folder scoring, confidence filtering, context headers, token truncation) runs exactly once on the final merged candidate set after the last tier is chosen.\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.0.1.3.md","text":"\n#### Memory merge could use stale data if the original changed during processing\n\nWhen merging two similar memories, the system reads the original memory, then sends it to an AI service for embedding generation (which involves a network call that can take seconds). After the embedding returns, the merge proceeds using the data it read earlier. But if another save modified or deleted that original memory during the embedding wait, the merge would overwrite the newer version with stale data -- or archive a record that no longer exists. Before committing the merge, the system now reloads the original memory inside the transaction and compares its content hash and last-modified timestamp against what it read before the embedding call. If the original changed, the merge aborts cleanly with a `predecessor_changed` status. If the original was deleted or archived by another process, it aborts with `predecessor_gone`. In both cases, the save falls through to the normal (non-merge) path instead of forcing stale data.\n\n\n#### Two index scans could start at the same time\n\nThe system prevents index scans from running too frequently using a cooldown timer. But the check was a classic \"time-of-check vs time-of-use\" race: read the last scan time, check if enough time has passed, then update the timestamp. Two requests arriving in the same millisecond could both pass the check and both start scanning, wasting resources and potentially conflicting. The cooldown is now an atomic lease. A single database transaction checks the timer and reserves the scan slot in one step -- if the lease is fresh, the request is rejected immediately. The lease includes a crash-expiry timer, so if a scan process dies mid-way, the slot is automatically freed after 2 minutes instead of being permanently locked.\n\n---\n\n## Search Performance\n\nThese fixes reduce redundant computation in the search pipeline. No search *results* change -- the same queries return the same answers, just faster.\n\n#### Fallback search was doing expensive work multiple times\n\nWhen a search doesn't find enough results, the system tries progressively looser criteria (\"fallback tiers\"). Each tier ran the *entire* search pipeline from scratch -- collecting candidates, fusing scores, reranking with the cross-encoder model, computing co-activation boosts, applying folder relevance, truncating by confidence, adding context headers, and trimming to token budget. The expensive post-processing stages (reranking, co-activation, token truncation) were running 2-3 times instead of once. The pipeline is now split into two phases. Phase 1 (collect and fuse candidates) runs for each fallback tier, building up the candidate pool. Phase 2 (reranking, co-activation, folder scoring, confidence filtering, context headers, token truncation) runs exactly once on the final merged candidate set after the last tier is chosen.\n\n\n#### Response size was estimated twice per result using slow serialization\n\nWhen deciding how many results fit in a response, the system estimates each result's \"token cost.\" It was calling this estimator twice per result -- once to compute the total, then again when greedily admitting results. Each call used `JSON.stringify()` to serialize the result object, which is surprisingly expensive for complex objects with nested metadata. Token estimates are now cached in a per-request map keyed by result ID. Each result is sized once and the cached value is reused. The estimator itself was rewritten to count known fields directly instead of serializing to JSON and measuring the string.","lineStart":20,"lineEnd":43,"totalLines":252,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.0.1.3.md","time":{"start":1781763870563,"end":1781763870566}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00e78b354ebe4379016a338f1d513481918022faa03b546d3c"}},"id":"prt_ed9670aa0001lLTEz8OXG5jImc","sessionID":"ses_126a03146ffe6yn9ha3tk3Qb0n","messageID":"msg_ed966ec7200118EoGiTDU6CDfd"}}
